channel.title: What to do with Dell Power Edge 2650?
channel.description:
Okay, well my aunt has given me a Dell Power-edge 2650 because she didn't need it and was going to trash it because it didn't have a pci-e 1x port to hook a certain expansion card; so apparently she has money out her ass. Me being sensible offered to take it off her hands, it has the following
Specifications: Two Intel Xeon 2.4ghz Processors 2GB Memory 2X SCSI 300GB 10,000 RPM Drives 1X SCSI 73GB 10,000 RPM Drive 2X Gigabit Lan Ports 3X PCI-X Slots Backwards Compatible with PCI cards
I am clueless as fuck with what to do with it. I was thinking about selling it and thought I could make a decent amount off it but i'm unsure. I was thinking $300 maybe? I have never evaluated servers for pricing so I don't know. What do you guys think I should do with it?

item.title: What to do with Dell Power Edge 2650?
item.dc:creator: @mwiebelhaus mwiebelhaus
item.description:
@mwiebelhaus wrote:

Moparisthebest:

Yea, nebraska wouldn’t be worth the drive if you paid me $100 to come get it. I wonder how much it would cost to ship, and if the hard drives would live.

I took the harddrives out, bubble-raped them and took them on carry on the plane. Shes going to be bringing the server at Christmas. So if you are interested in some SCSI harddrives i have:
2 new 300GB SCSI harddrives 10,000rpm
2 used 73GB SCSI harddrives 10,000rpm
drives

She had me put the 2 new ones in when I got to Nashville but decided she didn’t want the server so I pulled them back out and took it with me.

Some info:
The ones I labeled as new are Worldisk recertified by Fujitsu MXJ3300SC800600X 300GB SCSI drives
The other two are here http://www.amazon.com/Hitachi-Ultrastar-146Z10-IC35L073UCDY10-0-Centronics/dp/B0019MOYYQ they are used (or new) I am not sure if they shipped these new with the server or not.
